message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The presentation suggests injury to the deep peroneal nerve, which can lead to foot drop and decreased sensation in the first dorsal web space. The other nerves listed do not supply sensation or motor function to this area.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms of right foot drop and decreased sensation in the first dorsal web space indicate a common peroneal nerve (a branch of the sciatic nerve) injury, specifically the deep peroneal nerve. This nerve supplies the muscles that dorsiflex the foot and sensory fibers to the dorsal aspect of the foot.

The right unilateral foot drop and decreased sensation in the first dorsal web space suggests a deficit in the deep peroneal nerve, which innervates the muscles that dorsiflex the foot and evert the foot. The other options do not have these specific symptoms.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The presentation suggests a deficit in the deep peroneal nerve, which supplies the muscles that lift the foot and dorsiflex the ankle. The steppage gait is a compensatory mechanism used to lift the foot higher while walking. The superficial peroneal nerve supplies the lateral calf muscles and the sural nerve provides sensation to the lateral foot and ankle, while the tibial nerve supplies the posterior calf and foot muscles. None of these nerves are responsible for the presented deficit.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The presentation with right unilateral foot drop and decreased sensation in the first dorsal web space suggests a deficit in the deep peroneal nerve. This nerve innervates the muscles that dorsiflex the foot and toes and also provides sensation to the first dorsal web space. The superficial peroneal nerve supplies the lateral compartment of the leg and dorsal foot, the tibial nerve supplies the posterior compartment of the leg and plantar aspect of the foot, and the sural nerve supplies the lateral aspect of the foot and ankle.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The presence of foot drop and decreased sensation in the first dorsal web space indicates a deficit in the deep peroneal nerve, which innervates the muscles responsible for dorsiflexion and eversion of the foot as well as sensation in the first dorsal web space. The superficial peroneal nerve innervates muscles responsible for eversion and plantarflexion of the foot, while the tibial nerve innervates muscles responsible for plantarflexion, inversion, and sensation on the sole of the foot. The sural nerve provides sensory innervation to the lateral aspect of the foot and ankle.

The superficial peroneal nerve innervates the lateral compartment of the leg and foot, the tibial nerve innervates the posterior compartment of the leg and foot, and the sural nerve is a sensory nerve that innervates the lateral aspect of the leg and foot.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The presentation of a foot drop, decreased sensation in the first dorsal web space, and a steppage gait suggests a common peroneal nerve injury, specifically a deficit in the deep peroneal nerve. The superficial peroneal nerve affects the sensory innervation to the dorsum of the foot, but does not affect dorsiflexion. The tibial nerve affects plantarflexion of the foot and sensation over the sole of the foot, and the sural nerve affects sensation over the lateral aspect of the foot and calf.
